Shares of Johnson & Johnson JNJ, +1.57% rallied 2.5% in midday trading, enough to lift the Dow Jones Industrial Average DJIA, +2.99% into positive territory, after the consumer and healthcare products company said new tests on baby powder from a recalled bottle found no asbestos.
The stock's $3.24 price gain added 22 points to the Dow's price, which was up 20 points.
And an additional 48 laboratory tests, conducted by two third-party laboratories, on the single lot of baby powder that the company recalled on Oct. 18 confirmed that the powder did not contain asbestos.
"Rigorous and third-party testing confirms there is no asbestos in Johnson's Baby Powder," the company said in a statement.
The stock has gained 2.6% year to date, while the Dow Jones Industrial Average DJIA, +2.99% has advanced 16.1%.